@poetswithadhd YES! 

I also don't really think there's anything wrong with doing that??? 

Maybe I'm wrong, but I feel like it doesn't hurt anyone to romanticise my life

@Antoinette322 I've spent about the same for a private diagnosis that my NHS GP suddenly decided to no longer support.

...even though it was them who suggested I go private in the first place.

Absolute joke.

@FabPachirisu @3L_strugglebus That would kind of say a lot about their whole idea of ADHD then.

Like, I worked really hard on those forms, struggled through them.

Just because I was successful with them doesn't mean I didn't struggle and could have benefited from support.

@KatyBenson20 I'm inclined to agree.

I get the impression that the NHS believes ADHD is incredibly difficult to diagnose.

Compare my experience to that of my brother getting diagnosed in Canada directly by his GP &amp; getting support &amp; treatment immediately, who do you feel has had better care?

@HomeEdHub @seeing4d I really doubt it, to be honest, just given it was via phone call, not video call, and with a nurse, not a doctor.

But maybe.

Seems more likely it's just a poorly designed, inefficient system.

@peacelovewords @HermeticOpus Yep they asked about that a million times, and I’m just like…

Listen, I was extremely shy when I was a kid, I would never have gotten out of my seat b/c I would have been terrified of getting in trouble.

It is extremely common for ADHDers to mask their symptoms

@VerboseKate Yeah American healthcare is definitely worse.

I believe U.K. healthcare would be better if they banned the American-style private healthcare that is available alongside the NHS in the U.K.

 I paid a thousands for a private diagnosis 2 years ago and the level of care was shit

@Hannah_cannot Sounds cliche, but you gotta find what you like doing.

Like I love cycling. I love the feel of wind in my hair, whooshing down hills like a rollercoaster, dodging traffic, finding little spots in the city I’d never find in a car or on foot…

But I fucking hate lifting weights.

@dreamsofskies THIS! This is what I think the folks who doubt the existence of ADHD don't consider. 

Sure, everyone has trouble starting things they don't want to do sometimes, but DO YOU HAVE TROUBLE STARTING YOUR FAVOURITE THING???

DO YOU?

@Tallinier Maudsley in London says it provides services for  "areas with no attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) or autism spectrum disorder (ASD) services"

No idea how it works, and there's a 2 year waitlist, but might be worth looking into.

https://t.co/Bp5gxTgdUy

@4licerose @kyliesen94 I'm dealing with the same thing with my surgery. 

For me they changed the rules after I'd already been prescribed Elvanse on shared care, so they agreed to keep me on it, but I'm never allowed to adjust the medication, which... is not ideal.

Honestly stuck until NHS diagnosis

@yeahshewrites Aw thanks!

That’s totally fair, I tend to use it for that kinda thing too tbh!

Have you tried @focusmate ? That’s more 1 on 1 zoom calls, but on demand. (I’m too socially anxious to use it though, truthfully).

@Antlers_Bone @aaliyahmeeseeks I’m sorry you went through those experiences, that sounds truly awful.

I have to admit, what you’re saying doesn’t align with what I’ve read and been told by literal experts on ADHD, or with my own lived experience. 

I’m happy to be proven otherwise  if I’ve been misled.

@ADHD_Senpai @AskADHD I don’t disclose.

Since being self employed, I manage by setting strong boundaries with clients and being honest about what I can and cannot do.

As an employee I used to just play it off as part of my quirky, ‘eccentric creative” charm (while also asking for help).

@AdhdAngsty Oh my goooood, literally me!!! I do this EVERY SINGLE DAY! 

Like, "It's okay, you don't need to get stressed if you have a hard time getting going this morning."

20 mins later: "AAAAAAAH!!!!"

@GeoffBent I agree, self diagnosis is valid. For me, the official diagnosis gave me only two things: 

1. Access to medication (which was then taken away)
2. Not having the constant thought that I don't actually have ADHD, I'm actually just lazy (although I do still think this frequently)

@SCFGallagher I do co-working streams on Twitch.

Also I set most of my calls and meetings for first thing in the morning.

Also I just learned to try and set regular hours through how painful and annoying NOT doing it was.

@danidonovan @Miz_Soraya Okay, but hear me out, this is a perfectly legit tactic and the only way I ever manage to get my house clean. 

1. Move piles into different room
2. Move piles back into original room one by one so you’re not overwhelmed by all the piles at once

@itsjustfatimah As a Canadian living in the U.K…. You’re not half wrong. 

I never thought of myself as enthusiastic or positive until I moved here and started getting called that all the time. 

Expressing emotions is hard for British people.

@ClaraPLewis I wish I had a better answer, but I’m still struggling to figure this out for myself too. 

Only thing that has helped so far is noticing behaviours that I do on my own and then accepting and “practicing” them around others.

It’s a start!

@UndercoverAutie I used to live across from a private school and they would leafblow every single morning. 

Even in winter when there were no more leaves.

It was just… idk

@danialkalhori Go back to the methods I use for the rest of my life when I wasn't on meds I guess:
- Don't keep snacks around
- Stay busy

@Eliizzibeth 1. Plan what you want to do BEFORE it kicks in, or you may be taken on a wild ride of doing whatever seems interesting, even if it isn't important to you.

2. Get a good sleep. Sleep affects how it works big time.

3. It may not work as well around your period if you have one.

@BillWilliamsYYC @mat_schmaltz Toronto: 4,300 ppl/sq. km
Vancouver: 5,400 ppl/sq. I’m

Demand public housing now.

@dougkerrrrr @rclstudio This is super accurate. I wouldn't have ever been able to get my work to where I want it to be if I worked alone starting out. Now I have the experience to:
1. Be better at evaluating things objectively
2. Have the confidence to know exactly when/how/on what to ask for input on

@fochti Mostly my strategy is having friends who do not mind this.

I'll explain to them it's a coping mechanism I do, and apologies if it hurts them.

Also implementing batch responding to my texts every few days on a schedule for when I really fall off.

@coachcamg Having done both within a year of my diagnosis, I totally agree. 

Group - Get informed on the basics, get support from people just like you, including tips and tricks for managing ADHD, and realise you're not alone.

Coach - Work on issues and goals that are specific to you

@autie_anna ADHD Facebook is such a different vibe from ADHD Twitter, it's unreal.

Same with ADHD TikTok.

And don't even get me started on ADHD Reddit... such a dark place.

@drohno2 You're reading a lot into this that isn't there...

Literally just drawing a comparison between some poorly written fictional characters and the experience of being a woman with undiagnosed ADHD. 

Where did I say I wanted to be the trope? Lighten up dude.

@mlplaysthesims @MiddletonPlays 100%. 

All I can think about one day. 

Can't remember a thing about it the next.

@AdhdMayhem What do you hate about people? 

Do you hate every person all the time? Or is it that you hate some people? Or hate some people sometimes b/c they are unpredictable and don't always do what you'd like them to do?

b/c honestly I hate even my best friends sometimes, but not always
